# tldr

Example-first command help: a tldr page is a handful of real invocations for a
command, not the exhaustive prose of `man`. `show` is the lookup; `update`
refreshes the local cache; `platform` forces an OS-specific page. Reach for
`man` when you need the complete flag reference — tldr is for "remind me the
three ways people actually use `tar`."

| Recipe | Does |
|--------|------|
| `show` | the cheat-sheet page for a command |
| `update` | refresh the local page cache |
| `platform` | force a platform's page (linux/osx/windows) |
| `random` | a random page (discovery) |

Pages are community-maintained and offline once cached. When a command has
OS-specific behavior (`sed`, `date`, `ls`), `platform` pins the right variant —
handy for the GNU/BSD splits noted in @text/sed and @date/date. For interactive
fuzzy lookup, the cht.sh service fills the same niche with a search box.

```just
# the example-first cheat-sheet page for a command (default)
show command:
  tldr {{quote(command)}}

# refresh the local page cache
update:
  tldr --update

# force a platform's page: linux | osx | windows | sunos
platform os command:
  tldr --platform {{quote(os)}} {{quote(command)}}

# a random page, for discovery
random:
  tldr --random
```
